==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|nl|spook|t=ghost}}, from {{der|en|dum|spooc|t=spook, ghost}}. Cognate with {{cog|gml|spôk}}, {{m|gml|spûk|t=apparition, ghost}}, {{cog|gmh|gespük|t=a haunting}}, {{cog|de|Spuk}}, {{cog|da|spøge|t=to haunt}}, {{cog|sv|spöke|t=ghost}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|spo͞ok}}, {{IPA|en|/spuːk/}}
** {{audio|en|En-au-spook.ogg|a=AU}}
** {{rhymes|en|uːk|s=1}}
* {{enPR|spo͝ok}}, {{IPA|en|/spʊk/|ref={{R:en:McDavid:1979|13|116}}|aa=<<US>> <<dialectal>>}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[ghost]] or [[phantom]].
#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:ghost}}
#: {{ux|en|The building was haunted by a couple of '''spooks'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Doyle Land of Mist|passage="I'll say what I think, no more and no less, and I won't be scared by you or your '''spooks''' into altering my opinions."}}
# A [[hobgoblin]]. {{rfv-sense|en}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[scare]] or [[fright]].
#: {{ux|en|The big spider gave me a '''spook'''.}}
# {{lb|en|espionage|slang}} An [[undercover]] [[agent]], [[spy]]{{,}} or [[intelligence analyst]].
#* {{quote-web|en|date=24 July 2009|title=Spies like them|work=BBC News Magazine|passage=From Ian Fleming to John Le Carre - authors have long been fascinated by the world of espionage. But, asks the BBC’s Gordon Corera, what do real life '''spooks''' make of fictional spies?}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=Oct 13th 2012|work=The Economist|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21564585|title=Huawei and ZTE: Put on hold|passage=The congressional study frets that Huawei’s and ZTE’s products could be used as Trojan horses by Chinese '''spooks'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2025-09-23|title=Six books to read to understand Europe’s hard right|work=The Economist|url=https://www.economist.com/culture/2025/09/23/six-books-to-read-to-understand-europes-hard-right|issn=0013-0613|passage=The hard right is on the march in Europe. The Alternative for Germany, a party declared extremist by domestic '''spooks''', scored a record result in a national election in February.}}
# {{lb|en|slang|dated|offensive|ethnic slur}} A black person.
#* {{quote-av|en|year=1976|title=w:Taxi Driver|writer=w:Paul Schrader|role=Travis Bickle|actor=Robert De Niro|passage=Some won't take '''spooks'''—hell, don't make no difference to me.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Don Spears|title=Playing for Keeps|year=2002|month=February|publisher=Milligan Books|location=Los Angeles|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781881524526|isbn=1881524523|oclc=52631084|page=179|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781881524526/page/179|passage="{{...}} Dryades Street and that whole uptown neighborhood is gonna be worth a fortune once the white people take it back from you '''spooks''' and develop it. {{...}}"}}
# {{lb|en|philosophy}} A [[metaphysical]] [[manifestation]]; an [[artificial]] [[distinction]] or [[construct]].
#* {{quote-book|en|title2={{w|The Ego and Its Own|The Ego and His Own}}|author=w:Max Stirner|translator=Steven T. Byington|publisher2=Dover|year2=2005|year=1845|title=Der Einzige und sein Eigentum|passage=He who is infatuated with ''Man'' leaves persons out of account so far as that infatuation extends, and floats in an ideal, sacred interest. ''Man'', you see, is not a person, but an ideal, a '''spook'''.}}
# {{lb|en|US|slang|medicine}} A [[psychiatrist]].
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1975|author=Robert O. Pasnau|title=Consultation-Liaison Psychiatry|page=124
|passage=Commonly, the surgeons view nonsurgeons with disdain. The most disdain is directed toward the “shrinks” or the “'''spooks''',” as the psychiatrists are called.}}
# {{lb|en|slang|gambling}} A player who engages in [[hole carding]] by attempting to glimpse the dealer's [[hole card]] when the dealer checks under an ace or a 10 to see if a [[blackjack]] is present.

